Description: Make the compile-time default for ssl_groups tolerant of curves
 that don't resolve under the active OpenSSL provider set.

 PostgreSQL 18 introduced ssl_groups with a default of "X25519:prime256v1".
 Under a FIPS-only OpenSSL provider, X25519 is not registered (it is not a
 FIPS-approved curve) and OpenSSL's SSL_CTX_set1_groups_list parser bails on
 the first unknown entry, so postgres FATALs at startup with "could not set
 group names specified in ssl_groups: No valid groups found".

 Prefixing X25519 with '?' tells OpenSSL to silently skip the entry when it
 is not registered. In non-FIPS builds the curve resolves and is used as
 normal, so this is a no-op there. In FIPS-only builds the entry is skipped
 and prime256v1 (registered by the FIPS provider as the realname of
 secp256r1) becomes the active group, allowing the server to start.

 Upstream documents the FIPS incompatibility (commit db93988ab0, "doc: Add
 note to ssl_group config on X25519 and FIPS") but leaves the compile-time
 default unchanged, expecting operators to override it. OpenSSL itself ships
 every entry of TLS_DEFAULT_GROUP_LIST with '?' for the same reason.

--- a/src/backend/utils/misc/guc_tables.c
+++ b/src/backend/utils/misc/guc_tables.c
@@ -4851,7 +4851,7 @@ struct config_string ConfigureNamesString[] =
 		},
 		&SSLECDHCurve,
 #ifdef USE_SSL
-		"X25519:prime256v1",
+		"?X25519:prime256v1",
 #else
 		"none",
 #endif
--- a/src/backend/utils/misc/postgresql.conf.sample
+++ b/src/backend/utils/misc/postgresql.conf.sample
@@ -115,7 +115,7 @@
 #ssl_ciphers = 'HIGH:MEDIUM:+3DES:!aNULL'	# allowed TLSv1.2 ciphers
 #ssl_tls13_ciphers = ''	# allowed TLSv1.3 cipher suites, blank for default
 #ssl_prefer_server_ciphers = on
-#ssl_groups = 'X25519:prime256v1'
+#ssl_groups = '?X25519:prime256v1'
 #ssl_min_protocol_version = 'TLSv1.2'
 #ssl_max_protocol_version = ''
 #ssl_dh_params_file = ''
